{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1783301880,"nonce":"8KZJ+26aR84mVQKcxoDIKxukfHo=","title":"MySQL introspection corrupts ENUM/SET columns: the labels are force-uppercased.","message":"`crates/squealy-mysql/src/introspect.rs`: `sql_type` lowercases the full `COLUMN_TYPE`\n(`:522`), and any type without a dedicated branch — including `enum`/`set` — falls through to\n`_ =\u003e SqlType::Raw(column_type.to_uppercase())` (`:568`). So an\n`enum('active','inactive')` column reads back as `Raw(\"ENUM('ACTIVE','INACTIVE')\")` — the\nenum/set **member labels themselves are upper-cased**, silently changing the column's allowed\nvalues. Re-rendering that model would create a column whose valid set is `'ACTIVE'/'INACTIVE'`.\n\nThis is data-defining corruption, not just normalization: the `_` fallback must not case-fold a\ntype whose text carries string literals. ENUM/SET (and SET) should either be modelled with their\nexact labels or captured verbatim without altering case.\n\nFound in the introspection round-trip audit (see ~/.claude/plans/squealy-introspection-audit.md).","files":null}]}